<h1>Algebraic definition of a right angle</h1>

<p>In which through method of reason</p>
<p>
<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mrow>
    <msup>
      <mi>x</mi>
      <mi>n</mi>
    </msup>
    <mo>+</mo>
    <msup>
      <mi>y</mi>
      <mi>n</mi>
    </msup>
    <mo>=</mo>
    <mn>1</mn>
  </mrow>  
</math>
</p>
<p>is shown to trace a right angle as <em>n</em> approaches infinity</p>
<hr />
<p>
For this equation, it is clear that <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> when <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>, and vice versa, whether <em>n</em> is 1 or <em>n</em> is 10,000
</p>
<p>
</p>
<p>

Let's start with
<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math><br />
It traces a straight line from <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfenced><mn>0</mn><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math> to <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfenced><mn>1</mn><mn>0</mn></mfenced></math><br />
We are interested in the <strong>midpoint of this line</strong> - at what point are x and y equal?<br />
To solve, we can simply substitute x for y (since they are equal), so the equation becomes
</p><p>
<math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
  <mtable>
    <mtr>
      <mtd>
        <msup>
          <mi>x</mi>
          <mi>n</mi>
        </msup>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>x</mi>
          <mi>n</mi>
        </msup>
      </mtd>
      <mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd>
      <mtd>
        <mn>1</mn>
      </mtd>  
    </mtr>  
    <mtr>
      <mtd>
        <mn>2</mn>
        <msup>
          <mi>x</mi>
          <mi>n</mi>
        </msup>
      </mtd>
      <mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd>
      <mtd>
        <mn>1</mn>
      </mtd>  
    </mtr>  
    <mtr>
      <mtd>
        <mn>x</mn>
      </mtd>
      <mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd>
      <mtd>
  <mfrac>
    <mn>1</mn>
    <mroot>
      <mn>2</mn>
      <mi>n</mi>
    </mroot>  
  </mfrac>  
      </mtd>  
    </mtr>    
  </mtable>  
</math>
</p>
<p>
For <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>, this results in a midpoint at <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math>, which is intuitively correct<br /> 
The <em>n<sup>th</sup></em> root of 2 must necessarily approach 1 as <em>n</em> increases<br />
Therefore the inverse will also approach 1<br />
Restating, the value for which x and y are equal approaches 1 as <em>n</em> increases<br />
This has the effect of <strong>'pushing' the midpoint of the line towards the point <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfenced><mn>1</mn><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></strong>
</p>
<p>
Which will increasingly come to appear as a right angle, as <em>n</em> approaches infinity.<br />
QED, bitches
</p>
